{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:22:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:22:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.16,0.07,0.2,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90502"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of right loin pain radiating to her groin. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild tenderness on palpation of the right flank. Urine dipstick shows a trace of protein, trace of blood and is negative for nitrites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan reveals a 9 mm stone at her right pelvi-ureteric junction and an incidental 5 mm stone in the lower calyx of the left kidney. Further investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine 118 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum calcium (corrected) 2.55 mmol/L (2.10-2.60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urate 0.55 mmol/L (0.20-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary calcium excretion 0.55 mol/mol Cr (0.04-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArrangements are made for ureteroscopic retrieval of the 9 mm stone at the right pelvi-ureteric junction. The patient inquires about the management of the stone in the left kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management for the stone in the lower calyx of the left kidney?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leave alone and review in one year","Medical expulsion therapy","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Extracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy","Simultaneous ureteroscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has bilateral renal calculi: a symptomatic 9 mm stone at the right pelvi-ureteric junction requiring intervention, and an incidental asymptomatic 5 mm stone in the lower calyx of the left kidney. The management approach differs based on stone size, location, and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeave alone and review in one year\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for the small, asymptomatic left lower calyceal stone. Small renal calculi (less than 7 mm) that are not causing symptoms or obstruction can often be managed conservatively with periodic monitoring. Lower calyceal stones have a lower chance of spontaneous passage due to their dependent position, but at 5 mm, this stone poses minimal risk of complications if it remains stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical expulsion therapy\u003C/strong\u003E typically involves alpha-blockers to facilitate stone passage and is most effective for distal ureteric stones that are already in transit. It is not indicated for calyceal stones that are not obstructing the collecting system, as these medications would not help a stone pass from this location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure involving direct access to the kidney through a small incision in the flank. This approach is reserved for large stones (typically \u0026gt;20 mm), complex stone burdens, or stones resistant to other treatments. It would be overly aggressive for a small, asymptomatic 5 mm stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E uses focused shock waves to fragment stones and is a reasonable option for symptomatic renal stones. However, for an asymptomatic 5 mm stone, the risks of the procedure (including hematuria, pain, and potential kidney injury) outweigh the benefits, especially when conservative management is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous ureteroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would involve treating both stones during the same procedure. While this approach might be considered if both stones were symptomatic or if the asymptomatic stone was in the same kidney as the symptomatic one, it unnecessarily increases the complexity and risks of the procedure for an asymptomatic small stone in the contralateral kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s laboratory findings suggest hypercalciuria and hyperuricemia, which are risk factors for stone formation. These metabolic abnormalities should be addressed with dietary modifications and possibly medications to prevent future stone formation, regardless of the management approach chosen for the current stones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small (\u003C7 mm) renal tract calculi usually pass spontaneously and can be managed conservatively if asymptomatic.","Asymptomatic renal calculi in the lower calyx have a lower chance of spontaneous passage and can be monitored if small.","Management of renal calculi depends on size, location, symptoms, and associated complications."],"references":["Sorensen MD, Harper JD, Borofsky MS, et al. Removal of Small, Asymptomatic Kidney Stones and Incidence of Relapse. N Engl J Med 2022; 387:506-513. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa2204253","Sabler IM, Katafigiotis I, Gofrit ON, Duvdevani M. Present indications and techniques of percutaneous nephrolithotomy: What the future holds? Asian J Urol. 2018 Oct;5(4):287-294. doi: 10.1016/j.ajur.2018.08.004. Epub 2018 Sep 6. PMID: 30364501; PMCID: PMC6197369. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30364501/","Manzoor H, Saikali SW. Renal Extracorporeal Lithotripsy. In: StatPearls [online]. [Updated 2022 Jul 25]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560887/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T16:45:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T16:47:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108092"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"}